### Git - Git is a fast, open-source distributed version control system (VCS) designed to track changes in source code and files over time.
 With Git, every developer has a full copy of the project's history on their local machine. You can commit changes, view history, and switch branches entirely offline.
 You only need an internet connection when you want to share your changes with others.

* git init - Initializes a brand-new, empty Git repository in your current folder. #Initialized empty Git repository
* git status - Shows what's happening right now.
  git status -s #flag for short form, opposite of -verbose
* git add - Moves changes to the staging area.
 git add app.py #adds a file
 git add file1 file2 #adds multiple files
 git add . #adds everything current directory
 git add -A #adds everything current directory including deleted files
* git commit - Creates a snapshot. eg.git commit -m "Added login page" #saves progress
    #It only commits files that are already in the staging area (what you added with git add).
    #You have full control — you can choose which changes to include.
 git commit -am "message" (or -a -m) #The -a flag = --all
    # Git automatically does git add for all modified tracked files before committing.
    # Very convenient when you’ve only edited existing files and want to commit everything quickly.
   Best Practices
   - Use git commit -am when you’re sure you want to commit all changes to tracked files.
   - Use git commit -m when you want to be selective (recommended for bigger projects or team work).

*Git clone
syntax: git clone <repository-url> #git clone https://github.com/user/project.git
git clone https://github.com/user/project.git myapp #creates the clone and inserted in the file myapp

Clone Using SSH
git clone git@github.com:user/project.git
Requires SSH keys.
 - Advantages: No password prompts

Clone a Specific Branch: Normally, Git clones all branches and checks out the default branch.
- git clone -b development https://github.com/user/project.git
* git config - git config is Git’s command to view, set, and edit configuration settings. It controls almost everything in Git: your name/email,
 editor, default branch, aliases, colors, behavior, etc.
Configuration Levels (Very Important)
Git stores settings in 3 main layers. Higher layers override lower ones.
Level      Command Flag            Scope                 File Location        Use Case 
System      --system     All users on the computer       /etc/gitconfig    Admin-wide settings
Global      --global     Your user account (all repos)   ~/.gitconfig     Most common (name, email, editor)
Local       (default)    Only current repository         .git/config     (inside the repo)Repo-specific settings
# Rule of thumb: Use --global for your name and email.
--
git config --global user.name "Fawwaz"
git config --global user.email "fawwaz@example.com"
--
git config --global --list          # show all users 
git config --list                   # local + global (shows effective)
git config --list --show-origin     # shows which file each setting comes from
--
git config --global --unset user.email #remove user email and can also be used for name
git config --global --edit # opens an editor to edit user info
-- 
git config user.name #Verify it worked
git config user.email
-- 
(without --global):
Bashgit config user.name "Your Name"     # only current repositories
git config user.email "your@email.com"
--
# Default editor
git config --global core.editor "code --wait"     # VS Code
# or
git config --global core.editor "vim"

# Default branch name (main instead of master)
git config --global init.defaultBranch main

# Aliases (shortcuts)
git config --global alias.st status
git config --global alias.co checkout
git config --global alias.br branch
git config --global alias.lg "log --oneline --graph --all"

# Nice colors
git config --global color.ui auto


